Cases of Messenger chat where the Database and Web server layer need to work together: 

a. When user LOGS IN: 
--> take the user's login infor, create a POST request
--> Must search the database for user's name and credentials: ERROR IF NOT FOUND
--> ONLY IF name is found, Web server will perform authentication (for security)
--> authentication (will still leanr about Javalin's functionality), but could be through Twilio API, and send a code to their email account

b. When user wants to REGISTER: 
--> GUI should ask for relevant information: email, phone number, name, and store into variables
--> Web server will create a post request
--> web server will need to perform Authentication (sending code)
--> Web server will take user credentials, create variables from the JSON data
--> JDBC will store inside the database

c. When user wants to CREATE a new chat
--> GUI asks for new chat information (users)
--> sends via post request through the backend server
--> extract relevant information into variables
--> JDBC will take these variables and insert it as a new table in the database

d. When user wants access to an EXISTING chat
--> Send a POST request to the backend
--> the post request must contain the relevant information of the existing chat
--> turn the JSON info into variable data
--> variable data will be used to communicate with JDBC


NOTE: when it comes to POST requests, the GUI (JavaFX) must monitor user clicking of specific chats
--> depending on the chat that the user clicks, the web server will formulate the relevant post request with the relevant information


